"Kamachi M., Kuragano T., Yoshioka N., Zhu J., Uboldi F.","Assimilation of Satellite Altimetry into a Western North Pacific Operational Model",2001,"Advances in Atmospheric Sciences","18","5",,"767","786",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0038288533&partnerID=40&md5=d42384903944cedac7d23953f2d5bf4f","Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba 305-0052, Japan; Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Science, Beijing 100029, China; Magritte SNC, Milano, Italy","Kamachi, M., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba 305-0052, Japan; Kuragano, T., Meteorological Research Institute, 1-1 Nagamine, Tsukuba 305-0052, Japan; Yoshioka, N., Japan Meteorological Agency, 1-3-4 Otemachi, Tokyo 100-8122, Japan; Zhu, J., Institute of Atmospheric Physics, Chinese Academy of Science, Beijing 100029, China; Uboldi, F., Magritte SNC, Milano, Italy","An ocean data assimilation system, COMPASS-K (the Comprehensive Ocean Modeling, Prediction, Analysis and Synthesis System in the Kuroshio-region), has been developed at the Meteorological Research Institute (MRI). The purposes of the development are understanding ocean variability in the Kuroshio region as a local response to a global climate change with assimilated four-dimensional data sets, development of an operational system in the Japan Meteorological Agency, and for the GODAE (Global Ocean Data Assimilation Experiment) project The model is an eddy permitting version of an MRI-OGCM. Space-time decorrelation scales of ocean variability are estimated with TOPEX / POSEIDON (T / P) altimeter data. Subsurface temperature and salinity fields are projected from the T / P altimeter data with a statistical correlation method and are assimilated into the model with a time-retrospective nudging scheme. Seasonal variation in the western North Pacific is investigated. Realistic space-time distribution of the physical quantities, the path of Kuroshio and its separation from Honshu are captured well The Kuroshio volume transport is well reproduced in a reanalysis experiment of 1993. Preliminary predictability experiments are done in February and March, 1994. Predictability diagram shows the time scale of the predictability for temperature field is about 17 days in the Kuroshio south of Japan. This time scale is smaller than that in the North Atlantic.","Assimilation; Kuroshio; Predictability",,,,,,,"Adamec, D., Predictability of a quasi-geostrophic ocean flow; Sensitivity of varying model vertical resolution (1989) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 19, pp. 1753-1764; Anderson, D.L.T., Data assimilation in ocean models (1991) Max-Plank-Institute fuer Meteorologie, pp. 193-225. , M. Latif (Ed.), Strategies for Future Climate Research Hamburg, Germany; Arakawa, A., Computational design for long-term numerical integration of the equations of fluid motion: Two-dimensional incompressible flow, Part I (1966) J. Comp. Phys., 1, pp. 119-143; Arakawa, A., Lamb, V.R., Computational design of the basic processes of the UCLA general circulation model (1977) Methods in Comp. Phys., 17, pp. 173-265; Auer, S.J., Five-year climatological survey of the Gulf Stream system and its associated rings (1987) J. Geophys. Res., 92, pp. C11; Bennett, A.F., (1992) Inverse Methods in Physical Oceanography, 346p. , Cambridge University Press, Cambridge; Bourtier, F., Courtier, P., (1999) Data Assimilation Concepts and Methods, 75p. , Rep. of ECMWF; Brasseur, P., Blayo, E., Verron, J., Predictability experiments in the North Atlantic Ocean: Outcome of a quasi-geostrophic model with assimilation of TOPEX / POSEIDON altimeter data (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101, pp. 14161-14173; Bryan, K., A numerical method for the study of the world ocean (1969) J. Comp. Phys., 4, pp. 347-376; Carton, J.A., How predictable are the geostrophic currents in the recirculation zone of the north Atlantic? (1987) J. Phys. Ocenogr., 17, pp. 751-762; Cohn, S.E., An introduction to estimation theory (1997) J. Met. Soc., Japan, 75, pp. 257-288; Cooper, M., Haines, K., Altimetric assimilation with water property conservation (1996) J. Geophys. Res., 101, pp. 1059-1077; Courtier, P., Dual formulation of four-dimensional variational assimilation (1997) Q. J. Roy. Met. Soc., 123, pp. 2449-2461; De Mey, P., Robinson, A., Assimilation of altimeter eddy fields in a limited-area quasi-geostrophic model (1987) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 17, pp. 2280-2293; Gent, P.R., McWilliams, J.C., Isopycnal mixing in ocean general circulation model (1990) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 20, pp. 150-155; Haines, K., Dynamics and data assimilation in oceanography (1994) NATO ASI Series I, 19, pp. 1-32. , Data Assimilation: Tools for Modelling the Ocean in a Global Change Perspective, ed. by P.P. Brasseur and J.C.C. Nihoul; Hellerman, S., Rosenstein, M., Normal monthly wind stress over the world ocean with error estimates (1983) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 13, pp. 1093-1104; Hsieh, W., Modal bias in sea level and sea surface temperature, with application to remote sensing (1985) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 15, pp. 351-356; Imawaki, S., Uchida, H., Ichikawa, H., Fukasawa, M., Umatani, S., Time series of the Kuroshio transport derived from field observations and altimetry data (1997) Int. WOCE Newsletter, 25, pp. 15-18; Ishizaki, H., A simulation of the abyssal circulation in the North Pacific Ocean. Part I: Flow field and comparison with observations (1994) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 24, pp. 1941-1954; Ishizaki, H., Motoi, T., Reevaluation of the Takano-Oonishi scheme for momentum advection on bottom relief in ocean models (1999) J. of Atmos. Ocean. Tech., 16, pp. 1994-2010; Kagimoto, T., Yamagata, T., Seasonal transport variations of the Kuroshio: An OGCM simulation (1997) J. Phys. Oceanogr., 27, pp. 403-418; Kamachi, M., Toward assimilation of altimetry in combination with conventional data in the North Pacific Ocean (1995) Proceeding of Int. Workshop on Num. Pred. of Ocean. Cond.